Game Descriptor Concept:
build a weird combat machine, let it fight, learn from the wreckage, mutate the design

**Intent**

The replacement is not “better prompts.” It is a different authority model.

```text
Old model:
agent reads big manual
agent writes round plan / turn command JSON
server validates
renderer tries to make it look alive

New model:
server acts as game master
server gives legal choices
agent chooses actionId
server applies canonical payload
resolver emits semantic replay
renderer animates resolved truth
```

The agent’s job is strategy, not API composition, grid legality, schema compliance, or combat arbitration.

The human post-session loop is:

```text
Quit:
  end session, no save

Save:
  save champion design + fight dossier + shared debrief

Continue:
  save first, then start next session seeded with champion design
  both agents receive same shared debrief
  challenger gets bonus gold based on champion record
```

**Non-Negotiable Decisions**

- No backwards compatibility in final merged state.
- Remove `/round-plan` and `/turn-command`.
- Remove `submitRoundPlan` and `submitTurnCommand`.
- Remove public `submit_round_plan` and `submit_turn_command` action names.
- Do not ask the agent capability questions like “can you execute JS?” in gameplay flow.
- Keep combat simultaneous.
- Do not send rationale/internal thought to the server as combat truth.
- Public chat/trash talk is allowed but display-only.
- Private post-fight reflections are allowed only after at least one completed fight.
- Reflections stay private until consumed into the shared debrief.
- Champion design is private/carryover.
- Shared debrief is sent to both future agents.
- Challenger does not receive champion design.
- V1 is perfect-information tactics. Do not half-build fog-of-war.

**New Agent Connection Prompt**

Replace the current giant manual with a short static brief in [agentBrief.ts](/C:/Users/Steve/Documents/Github/portfolio/apps/web/src/agent/agentBrief.ts) and [agentContract.ts](/C:/Users/Steve/Documents/Github/portfolio/packages/schemas/src/agentContract.ts).

Example:

```text
You are about to play Clash of Clankers.

Declare:
- agentName
- teamIdentity.name
- teamIdentity.colorHex as valid hex
- teamIdentity.logoPrompt or logo asset

Preferred browser path:
Open /agent#session=<id>&role=<red|blue>&claimToken=<token>&api=<base>
Then call:
await window.AgentArenaRole.bootstrapRole({ agentName, teamIdentity })

Raw HTTP fallback:
POST /sessions/:sessionId/roles/:role/bootstrap
Authorization: Bearer <claimToken>

After bootstrap, follow the returned GameMasterPacket.
Choose from legalActions and submit actionId only.
```

No old examples that tell agents to build custom v2 plans or inspect `movementOptions.recommended`.

**New Public Routes**

Keep:

```text
POST /sessions/:sessionId/roles/:role/bootstrap
GET  /sessions/:sessionId/state
GET  /sessions/:sessionId/public
GET  /sessions/:sessionId/replay
POST /sessions/:sessionId/chat
POST /sessions/:sessionId/private-chat
```

Add:

```text
POST /sessions/:sessionId/action
POST /sessions/:sessionId/reflection
POST /sessions/:sessionId/save
POST /sessions/:sessionId/continue
POST /sessions/:sessionId/quit
```

Remove:

```text
POST /sessions/:sessionId/round-plan
POST /sessions/:sessionId/turn-command
```

`/advance-round` is not automatically legacy. If the game still supports multiple fights/rounds inside one session, keep it as human/referee round control. If the new model collapses each session to one completed fight, then remove it too. Do not decide that accidentally.

**Core Contracts**

Add/replace schema in [types.ts](/C:/Users/Steve/Documents/Github/portfolio/packages/schemas/src/types.ts) and [relay.ts](/C:/Users/Steve/Documents/Github/portfolio/packages/schemas/src/relay.ts).

```ts
type GameMasterPhase =
  | 'wait_for_opponent_claim'
  | 'choose_loadout'
  | 'wait_for_opponent_loadout'
  | 'combat_turn'
  | 'wait_for_opponent_turn'
  | 'replay_phase'
  | 'round_review'
  | 'session_complete'
  | 'expired';

type GameMasterPacket = {
  sessionId: string;
  role: TeamRole;
  phase: GameMasterPhase;
  nextAction: GameMasterNextAction;
  round: number;
  fightId?: string;
  turnId?: string;

  decisionVersion: number;
  eventVersion: number;
  actionSetId?: string;

  instruction: string;
  resources?: AgentResourcesView;
  catalog?: CatalogSnapshotView;
  board?: AgentBoardView;
  visibleState?: AgentVisibleCombatState;
  legalActions: GameMasterLegalAction[];

  sharedDebrief?: SharedDebrief;
  submit?: SubmitInstruction;
};
```

Use separate versions:

```ts
type VersionContract = {
  decisionVersion: number; // snapshot both agents choose from
  actionSetId: string;     // exact role-specific legal menu
  eventVersion: number;    // chat/replay/public-state progression
};
```

`stateVersion` alone is not enough. If red submits first and increments state, blue’s simultaneous action must not become stale.

**Legal Action Contract**

```ts
type GameMasterLegalAction = {
  id: string;
  kind:
    | 'select_loadout'
    | 'buy_part'
    | 'place_part'
    | 'confirm_loadout'
    | 'move'
    | 'attack'
    | 'move_and_attack'
    | 'use_utility'
    | 'hold'
    | 'ready';

  label: string;
  summary: string;

  catalogRefs?: string[];
  requirements?: string[];

  preview?: {
    basis: 'current_snapshot';
    outcome: 'estimated' | 'guaranteed';
    path?: GridCoord[];
    finalPose?: BotPose;
    target?: GridCoord;
    currentLineOfSight?: boolean;
    expectedRangeIfOpponentHolds?: number;
    hazardExposure?: number;
    riskTags?: string[];
  };
};
```

Do not expose canonical payloads to agents.

Server stores:

```ts
type ActiveActionSet = {
  actionSetId: string;
  role: TeamRole;
  phase: GameMasterPhase;
  round: number;
  fightId?: string;
  turnId?: string;
  decisionVersion: number;
  catalogVersion: string;
  arenaVersion: string;
  createdAt: string;
  expiresAt?: string;

  actions: Record<string, CanonicalGameAction>;

  locked?: {
    actionId: string;
    submittedAt: string;
    requestHash: string;
  };
};
```

Submission:

```ts
type GameMasterActionSubmission = {
  action: 'submit_game_action';
  actionSetId: string;
  decisionVersion: number;
  actionId: string;
  publicMessage?: string;
};
```

Accepted example:

```ts
{
  action: 'submit_game_action',
  actionSetId: 'red:r1:f1:t3:v12',
  decisionVersion: 12,
  actionId: 'combat.red.r1.f1.t3.move_east_2.fire_weapon_a',
  publicMessage: 'Your left side is looking soft.'
}
```

Rejected forever:

```ts
{
  actionId: 'combat.red.r1.f1.t3.move_east_2.fire_weapon_a',
  move: { x: 2, z: 0 },
  weaponA: { target: 'blue' },
  rationale: 'I want to flank...'
}
```

The server ignores/blocks client-authored gameplay payloads.

**Loadout / Builder Phase**

The catalog must come from the existing catalog package, not a new JSON schema.

Relevant files:

- [parts.ts](/C:/Users/Steve/Documents/Github/portfolio/packages/catalog/src/parts.ts)
- [capabilities.ts](/C:/Users/Steve/Documents/Github/portfolio/packages/catalog/src/capabilities.ts)
- [controls.ts](/C:/Users/Steve/Documents/Github/portfolio/packages/catalog/src/controls.ts)
- [blueprint.ts](/C:/Users/Steve/Documents/Github/portfolio/packages/catalog/src/blueprint.ts)
- [inventory.ts](/C:/Users/Steve/Documents/Github/portfolio/packages/catalog/src/inventory.ts)

The loadout phase is a permissive, server-guided freeform builder. Agents should be able to create unusual modular bots through legal builder actions: central wheels, weapons attached to odd targets, long strut arms, asymmetric armor, counterweights, and ugly-but-legal machines.

The server remains authoritative. Agents do not submit raw blueprint JSON. They submit action IDs for each builder step. The server stores and applies the canonical placement payload.

Part behavior comes from the catalog, not placement fantasy:
- A laser mounted near/on a wheel is still a laser.
- A wheel with a laser attached does not become a turret unless the catalog defines that behavior.
- A frame strut extends structure but does not add mobility.
- Armor absorbs damage but does not become a weapon.
- Counterweight changes mass/handling only if that behavior exists; otherwise it is ballast/structure.

Builder flow:

1. choose part
2. choose attach target
3. choose mount side / attach cell
4. choose rotation
5. server places part
6. repeat / remove / move / rotate
7. confirm loadout

Do not generate every possible part x cell x rotation combination in one packet. Each packet should expose only the legal choices for the current builder step.

Example: 
```js
{
  phase: 'choose_loadout',
  nextAction: 'build_bot',
  instruction: 'Choose a part to add to your bot.',
  decisionVersion: 7,
  actionSetId: 'red:r1:builder:choose_part:v7',
  resources: {
    gold: 100,
    remainingGold: 74,
    partLimitRemaining: 8
  },
  buildState: {
    step: 'choose_part',
    currentDesign: {
      rootInstanceId: 'part_1',
      parts: [
        {
          instanceId: 'part_1',
          partId: 'Body_Light_Frame',
          cell: { x: 0, z: 0 },
          rotation: 0
        }
      ]
    }
  },
  catalog: {
    version: 'catalog-2026-06-07',
    parts: '<existing PART_CATALOG entries or compact catalog view with real specs/metadata>'
  },
  legalActions: [
    {
      id: 'build.red.r1.choose_part.Frame_Strut',
      kind: 'choose_part',
      label: 'Frame strut',
      summary: 'Cheap connector for extending the bot frame.',
      catalogRefs: ['Frame_Strut']
    },
    {
      id: 'build.red.r1.choose_part.Weapon_Laser',
      kind: 'choose_part',
      label: 'Laser',
      summary: 'Ranged weapon. Keeps laser behavior regardless of mount target.',
      catalogRefs: ['Weapon_Laser']
    }
  ],
  submit: {
    method: 'POST',
    path: '/sessions/:sessionId/action',
    body: {
      action: 'submit_game_action',
      actionSetId: 'red:r1:builder:choose_part:v7',
      decisionVersion: 7,
      actionId: '<legalActions.id>'
    }
  }
}
```

placement example: 
```js
{
  phase: 'choose_loadout',
  nextAction: 'build_bot',
  instruction: 'Choose where to attach Weapon_Laser.',
  decisionVersion: 8,
  actionSetId: 'red:r1:builder:attach_target:v8',
  buildState: {
    step: 'choose_attach_target',
    selectedPartId: 'Weapon_Laser',
    catalogVersion: 'catalog-2026-06-07',
    currentDesign: {
      parts: [
        { instanceId: 'part_1', partId: 'Body_Light_Frame' },
        { instanceId: 'part_2', partId: 'Wheel_Omni' }
      ]
    }
  },
  legalActions: [
    {
      id: 'build.red.r1.attach.Weapon_Laser.to.part_1.north',
      kind: 'choose_attach_target',
      label: 'Attach laser to body north mount',
      summary: 'Mounts laser from the body frame.'
    },
    {
      id: 'build.red.r1.attach.Weapon_Laser.to.part_2.top',
      kind: 'choose_attach_target',
      label: 'Attach laser to omni wheel top mount',
      summary: 'Unusual placement. Laser remains a laser; wheel remains a wheel.'
    }
  ]
}
```

Builder DSA: 
```text
input:
  role state
  gold
  current draft design
  selected builder step
  selected part/target/rotation, if any
  catalog snapshot
  champion carryover design if continuing

process:
  read existing PART_CATALOG and part metadata
  build legal next-step actions only
  validate remove/move/rotate actions from active action set
  preserve at least one connected root after removal
  validate affordability
  validate part count
  validate graph connectivity
  validate server-created part instance IDs
  validate mount/attach target from active action set
  validate rotation from active action set
  validate minimum viable bot on confirm
  store canonical payload per actionId

output:
  GameMasterPacket.buildState
  GameMasterPacket.legalActions
  ActiveActionSet.actions
```

```text
Filler parts must have cost, mass, durability, category, attach affordances, render classification, and sim behavior. They must not add active weapon/mobility/utility behavior unless explicitly defined in the catalog.
Structural filler parts are required so weird builds have enough connective tissue:
- Frame_Strut
- Mount_Plate
- Spacer_Block
- Armor_Tile
- Counterweight
```

**Combat DSA**

Add or extract:

```text
packages/sim/src/gameMasterActions.ts
packages/sim/src/combatActions.ts
packages/sim/src/loadoutActions.ts
packages/sim/src/actionIds.ts
packages/sim/src/gridMovement.ts
packages/sim/src/combatLegality.ts
```

Core flow:

```text
session state
  -> role private view
  -> action builder
  -> active action set
  -> agent chooses actionId
  -> SessionCoordinator locks selected canonical payload
  -> when both roles locked, resolver consumes canonical payloads
  -> ReplayTimeline.events
```

V1 movement legality is tactical-grid based:
```text
bot anchor cell
movement budget
arena bounds
blocked center cells
path cannot pass through blocker cells
hazard cells crossed by anchor path
occupied anchor-cell conflicts
line of sight from final anchor cell
weapon range from final anchor cell
```
V1 intentionally does not enforce bot footprint, swept volume, rotation volume, or visual part clipping. Oversized bot geometry may clip in replay. That is acceptable because tactical anchor cells are the combat truth.

Conflict rules must be deterministic:

```text
both enter same cell
paths cross
both bots choose same anchor cell
paths cross anchor cells
one bot rams while one holds
attack target moves out of range
line of sight changes after movement
hazard exposure from anchor path
bot destroyed before firing
one bot rams while one holds
attack target moves out of range
line of sight changes after movement
hazard push/drag outcome
bot destroyed before firing
```

Recommended resolution order:

```text
1. validate selected canonical intents
2. resolve movement and collisions
3. apply hazard exposure
4. resolve weapon fire from final poses
5. resolve utility/detach/end effects
6. emit replay timeline
```

